Russian President Vladimir Putin has signed a law imposing administrative responsibility for violation of the term and order of payment of goods (works, services) in the implementation of purchases for state and municipal needs.
This law is designed to address the very acute problem of customers' defaults in public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation when entrepreneurs could not get paid under already executed state and municipal contracts, was widespread.
At the same time, the Russian president instructed the Russian Prosecutor General's Office to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who concluded contracts not backed by financing, tried to evade the obligations of payment and included in the contracts illegal conditions.
The problem was systemic in general in the country.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, the Prosecutor's Office has made 9.7 thousand submissions, as a result of their consideration, 4,500 officials have been brought to disciplinary responsibility, 533 to the administrative ones, 75 materials have been submitted to the investigative bodies for organizing procedural checks, 46 of them have been prosecuted.
As a result, the debt to entrepreneurs amounting to more than 66 billion rubles was repaid.
And these huge sums were not accumulated as a result of non-payment of multibillion-dollar contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in paying services to entrepreneurs for much more modest sums led to fabulous debts.
Here's a typical case.
The head of a small company won a competition to provide services for social transportation for several million rubles.
The man invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled the obligations, but did not receive the money in time.
The result is a growing financial com of debts on salaries, taxes, loans, which would lead to bankruptcy, if the entrepreneur did not apply for help to the prosecutor's office.
Now in a number of regions the problem has been leveled as much as possible.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts, identified by prosecutors of the subjects of the Russian Federation, amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical levels, the prosecutor's office operates in a manual anti-crisis management regime.
The Attorney-General personally holds field meetings with local authorities, where all violations uncovered by prosecutors are dealt with and measures to address them immediately.
Such operational meetings have already taken place in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg this year.
The implementation of Federal Law No. 189-Fz "On amending the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences in terms of establishing the administrative responsibility of customer officials for violation of the term and order of payment of goods (works, services) in the implementation of purchases for the provision of state and municipal needs" will be able to improve the payment of public customers.
The draft law was developed by the Russian Ministry of Economic Development on the initiative of the Prosecutor General's Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences with an article, which provides for a fine of 30,000 to 50,000 rubles for violation of the term and payment of goods, works and services in state and municipal procurements.
And if an official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the subjects of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative novels in practice.
Civil rights group announces travel warning in Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to people of color traveling to Missouri because of discriminatory state policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The National Association for the Advancement of Colored Travel, valid until August 28, 2017, encourages African-American travelers, visitors and citizens of Missouri to be particularly careful and to exercise increased caution when traveling across the state in response to a number of controversial racist incidents that have recently occurred throughout the state and are brought here."
According to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the group's recent law in Missouri made it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, and that state law enforcement disproportionately choose minorities as their targets, according to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
"People are being violated by human rights.
They are stopped on the roads because of their skin color, they are beaten and killed," Rod Chapel, president of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People of Missouri, told the Kansas City Star newspaper.
"We hear complaints more often than ever before."
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization to the U.S. state.
The group cited incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of 20-year-old Tori Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gasoline during a state trip, and Missouri State Police arrested him without charge of a crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General's Office, which found that black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than whites.
"The purpose of the warning is to keep people informed of the situation and to warn their family and friends and colleagues about what could happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
"People should be prepared in one way or another, whether they take the money with them for bail or tell their relatives that they are traveling across the state."
According to the latest data from the FBI's Hate Crime Report Program, There were 100 hate crimes recorded in Missouri in 2015, making the state the 16th largest state in the number of such violations.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that will make it more difficult to bring a case against a legal entity for housing or labor discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued warnings to travelers in Texas and Arizona after those states passed new immigration control laws requiring local law enforcement to arrest people for immigration violations, which the ACLU said should have increased the number of racially motivated background checks.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
