Nothing sacred?
Now the Trump White House is targeting the Statue of Liberty.
The surest sign of regime change is when he begins to fight the statues.
Americans understand this no worse than everyone else - hence the deliberate theatrical demolition of a statue of Saddam Hussein in Baghdad's Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the Trump administration's key ideologues, no doubt knew what he was doing when he blew a symbolic axe over the Statue of Liberty during a bitter dispute with CNN journalist Jim Acosta about the president's proposals to drastically reduce legal migration.
Let's be honest, Miller didn't try on the statue itself.
The hordes of pleasure boat owners and artists depicting the Statue of Liberty would lynch him if he tried to do so.
But he tried to make sense of it, and especially the meaning that was attributed to it in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument, when Emma Lazarus's poems were added to the pedestal.
As Miller grumbled at Acosta: "I don't want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you are talking about was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller correctly laid out the facts, but as he himself said, it's not really about the story.
It's about the current sound of the startling words of Lazarus, the only ones in which the state invites not any immigrants, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / your crowds, dreaming to breathe freely, / The unfortunate dregs of your abundant shores."
Never before have "unfortunate garbage" been so visible on our screens.
Miller wasn't involved in literature - he made it clear that in Trump's America, these people aren't expected.
This debate about the meaning of the statue is part of a broader political and cultural war: it's really a debate about the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends who fought to put her words on the plinth of the statue after her death - were very well aware that they were committing a completely political act.
The sculpture was intended to mark the connection between the French and American republics with the help of a banal classical figure - the female image of Liberty.
Lazarus changed her meaning: in her poem the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a completely different name: The Mother of the Exiles.
The combination of the poem and the image was a brilliant feminist move and a crushing attack against American nativism.
And how Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right though change it back.
The vociferous Rush Limbaugh, the sort of John the Baptist who heralded Trump's coming, in 2010 reasoned that Freedom does not invite anyone, rather it is an early neoconservative who carries the flames of America lying in the darkness of the world: "Freedom goes forward.
It carries the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not needed to illuminate the path to the United States."
Against the habit of Limbaugh here really got to the point.
The meaning of the statue depends solely on the angle of view.
Lazarus's great creative achievement was to see her as seen by the exhausted, unhappy but hopeful people on the decks of the ships after a long and often hard voyage.
It means literally looking at the world through the eyes of people who are seeking refuge and a chance for a better life.
Her statue responds to them with words of hope and hospitality that they dream of hearing.
And, of course, that's not the kind of prospect that Miller and Trump will ever want to accept.
Their torch is needed not to illuminate the path, but to incite hatred, which is the only source of their power.
