Facebook critics: Don't run for public office if you're not willing to listen to criticism from voters
The founder of our country understood what a critical press is.
Americans loved George Washington, but that didn't stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism of him, of course, irritated.
But he didn't shut his mouth to his critics.
Because as far back as 1783, Washington said, "you can take away the freedom of speech and we, deaf and dumb, will lead like sheep to the slaughterhouse."
Now I'm going to turn to Maryland Gov. Larry Hogan, who should have tried to be more like Washington.
Hogan's subordinates blocked and erased the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's subordinates called the lawsuit insignificant, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of "well and what."
"It's just Facebook," many will say.
But it's also important.
And that's especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He's a surprisingly popular Republican governor in the Democratic primary state.
He is in second place in the approval rating among 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a staunch reactionary.
He has shown a firm hand in the management of the state and a commitment to his principles.
He also deftly uses Facebook as a primary way to connect with his constituents and with jokes showing off his bald post-chemotherapy head on his page.
So blocking people who come to the governor's page - which is billed as an official public forum and run by administration officials with taxpayer money - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with The Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Chas defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking the comments was simply their moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and haters, angry on the Internet.
The Post spoke to some of the real people that Hogan blocked.
And these are real people, not trolls - a teacher, a businessman, a pastor who appeals to their elected leaders.
All of them say that their comments were respectful, informative and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing that Hogan was Catholic.
Lakshmi's attorney, Sarma Raman of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hate but asked about the hate crimes.
"I have made a polite comment that I am disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news," she wrote in the comments section of the Post article.
"I also don't like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it's a so-called twist, instead of admitting to having to deal with a large group of disgruntled citizens."
What the governor's subordinates call a "concentrated spam attack", others would probably call "active life position."
In the era of Facebook, it's easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
It's a much less dusty job than it used to be, when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical editorials, or arresting and shutting the mouths of protesters.
But that's exactly what's happening now, only in numbers.
Hogen is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social media.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who have been banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, pivotal decisions on the topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James K. Casherys of Alexandria, the chairman of the Loudon County Supervisory Board violated the First Amendment by locking a voter on his Facecbook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Gov. Matt Bavin sued the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington's time, the era of affordable postal spending has taken about the same upheaval as the Internet today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters greatly destroyed its authority.
And even then, Washington dealt with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms Yurikola, Valerias, Belizerius and Porousius wrote letters to newspapers ridiculing Washington's decision.
According to historical documents collected by the online project "George Washington Documents", his office was inundated with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Friendship, Trade and Navigation.
But he didn't try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lies at the very core of our state.
And true leadership means accepting it.
