Poverty and death in Indonesian "golden land"
While cooking lunch, Bardin Degai does not use the stove.
She even uses pot rarely.
In her wooden home in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, a housewife usually simply places a sweet potato, which is called "note", right in the hearth.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is taken out and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degay sits on the earthen floor - she doesn't have furniture - and it is here that she does her chores, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The restroom serves as a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband's four wives, so she was not assigned to work in the field.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men from this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
"No one dares to walk around the village after five in the evening," she says.
It is a rare opportunity to look at daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote in public raising their hands in front of occupying troops.
The existing pro-independence movement from the Netherlands quickly drew its ire against the Jakarta government, which maintains tight control over the region, preventing foreign journalists and human rights defenders from being allowed.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as it is abandoned; The road here includes an hour-and-a-half flight from Jayapura, the provincial capital, to Nabir, and then a five-hour shaking on a hired car.
There is no public transport here.
The city of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; roofed corrugated steel is painted with rust in a variety of reddish shades.
Few Indonesians, let alone journalists, and almost none of the foreigners got here.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, Papuans worshipped a god named Uga Tamae.
There were other changes.
"It was unusual for us to wear these clothes," Degay says, pointing to his bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
"We used to wear only leaves on the body."
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
But it's also Indonesian gold land.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Paniai, a high-altitude province about the size of New Jersey, home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined about $3.1 billion in gold and copper.
In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves estimated at $78 billion.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful armed forces maintain their suffocating presence here.
According to a New York Times investigation in 2005, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local military personnel and units between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 to an officer.
The demands for greater autonomy on the part of the Papuans threaten the existence of this gold mine and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by the Indonesian military since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, mass killings in indigenous people in the highlands of Papua in the seventies can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
"We will lose everything," a report published in 2016 by the Brisbane Diocese, contains evidence of atrocities committed the previous year, such as non-trial executions, torture - especially frequent, according to another report, rape and electric shock - and brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because there are incidents every week," said Andreas Harsono, a research researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The nuts dragged on as Papua's resources attracted an influx of migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's 3.5-million-strong population is 83 percent Christian, but demographics change as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese shops, "varungs", sell fried chicken and a mixture of vegetables "godo-gado" served with peanut sauce.
Locals are trying to withstand the competition.
"Migrants started selling chicken and vegetables in the traditional market cheaper than the natives of Papua," explains Abet Jou, a twenty-four-year-old paniai native who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, because of work.
"Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua - the mother-mother (women) of Papua - have lost their market."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokomi, vowed to tackle inequality and rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Paniai.
But in Papua almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokoie, expecting him to fulfill our hopes for justice," says You.
In fact, just two months after Jokoi Paniai's October inauguration, he experienced a tragedy.
On 7 December 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas carols by a fire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke out of the darkness.
Terrified children told them they should turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Javedt Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and returned with four soldiers a short time later.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, soldiers who were drunk were chasing children and beating them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julianus Eimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A couple of hours later, someone set fire to a nearby government election commission building, and the next day the situation escalated.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of a local police station and a military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed the White, a dance of the Papuan mee pago tribe: they ran in circles and depicted bird singing.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and military base.
When the situation was tense, the soldiers were ordered by internal radio: "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them," as stated in the official document seen by TIME correspondents, but which was not published in local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Jeremiah Koyame, head of the Kego Coto district in Enorotali, felt the danger was approaching and called for calm, asking the crowd to go home.
No one wanted to listen to him.
"When I turned, I was suddenly hit in the left wrist by a bullet," he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly colored wooden house.
Koyame still does not know who fired, but says that the bullet came from the side of the assembled soldiers.
"There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots," he adds.
A local resident, AlfieS Jouw, was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," Johannes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name, told TIME.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
General Jotje Mende, a senior inspector of Papua police, told reporters that his officers were merely "protecting" their base because it was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," Papua police spokesman Commissioner Pujo Sulistyo said in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were wounded.
News of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokoi delivered an impassioned speech in Jayapur in which he expressed condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to address the historic abuse of power in Papua.
"I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it will never happen again in the future," he said.
In October 2016, Minister for Security Viranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to end historical human rights violations.
But almost immediately there were excuses.
"Most of the violations occurred a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or early zeros.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be passed," he said.
Viranto then retracted his remarks, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he had no plans to set up an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, "Everything will be decided through the courts."
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of "crimes against humanity" in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people in the bloody vote for East Timor's independence in 1999, said 11 human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the Victims of Paniai met with grim incredulity.
"I've been questioned four times in the last three years, but there's been no change at all," says Johannes.
"I'm tired."
He says that years later he still lives in fear.
"I'm scared," he says.
"I'm afraid I'll be arrested by the military, I'm afraid I'll be shot."
His brother Jacobus also suggested that the people of Paniai were afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping to bury the four victims.
"After we buried the bodies, the military came for me," he said.
The shooting didn't stop.
