"I hid at home for two days."
The Deiyai Parliament demanded that the officers involved in the incident be called to account and the mobile police brigade withdrawn from the region.
Paniyai has always been a sore spot for the Indonesian government.
The lack of significant development is caused by discontent of the tribes of mee, moni, tributes and damal, scattered throughout the territory of the green-covered central highland districts of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), an insurgent army that claims to protect the rights of Papuans by staging sporadic attacks and kidnapping attacks on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of OPM's top executives come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Kogoya.
In response to the recent years, thousands of people have been arrested and detained by the military in Paniai on the pretext of "protecting national independence".
Some never came back.
Among the population of Papua Paniai is considered a "sad, forgotten place."
Poverty increases discontent.
A small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for locals.
