A day after a lawsuit by 15 states, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency reversed his decision to delay obama-made regulations designed to reduce emissions of air pollutants that lead to smog.
Pruitt explained his decision by saying that his agency now listens more to the needs of individual state environmental regulators than under previous administrations.
He made no mention of a lawsuit against his previous position filed in federal appeals court.
The dispute revolved around the October 1 deadline by which states must meet the 2015 ozone-level standards.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would delay compliance for one year to give his agency more time to study the plan and avoid "inconsistencies with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth."
Pruitt, who was Oklahoma's attorney general before being appointed by President Trump, has long been known as a consistent opponent of tougher environmental regulations.
Since moving to Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly blocked or delayed the introduction of regulations opposed by the chemical or gas and gas industries.
Wednesday's sudden change of course is another legal defeat of Pruitt's policy of reversing the old standards.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA chief overstepped his authority in trying to delay the Obama administration's implementation of a rule requiring oil and gas companies to track and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt suggested that by abruptly changing course on ozone standards, he simply complied with the EPA's responsibility to cooperate with states in a comprehensive process for timely enforcement of the new standards.
"Under previous administrations, the EPA has often failed to meet schedule, then waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others to discuss the timing of the settlement," said Pruitt, who has filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
"We do not believe in regulation through litigation, and we take the deadlines seriously.
We also take seriously our charter and the power it gives us."
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt may at some point re-use his "powers to delay and other data by law" to make sure the rules "jcyjdfys are on a clear course and on all available information."
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader overhaul of ozone regulations.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on the issue.
