The order and places of swearing will be determined by the president
Where and how the new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the president - such amendments to the second reading in the relevant law developed by the State Duma Committee on Law and State Construction.
A week ago, the deputies planned to directly determine the procedure of swearing in the law.
Children under the age of 18 will be exempt from taking a solemn oath, as well as incapacitated children, according to the revised text of amendments to the bill "On the citizenship of the Russian Federation" (there is at the disposal of "Izvestia"), which the committee will consider on July 11 before the second reading at its meeting.
President Vladimir Putin supported the idea of taking the oath of office when he became a citizen of the Russian Federation instead of formally signing the documents on June 6 during a meeting with State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
The MPs drafted this idea as an amendment to the second reading of the bill providing for the abolition of the decision to grant citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public calls to terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (v. 2 p. 205.2 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation), as well as for the hijacking of an airplane trains or water transport, but only if this act is related to terrorism (v. 4 p. 211 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
According to the bill, his logic was this: by issuing documents for citizenship, a person signs under a promise to comply with Russian law - embarking on the path of extremism, he breaks this promise.
The bill was introduced to the State Duma in April by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasilyev ("United Russia"), Gennady Syuganov (CPRF), Vladimir Jirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov ("Fair Russia") and the speaker of the DG Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies adopted it in the first reading.
Last week, the DG Committee on State Construction and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but now it has been reworked again.
Now it says that the order of swearing is set by the President of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, the parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law on russian citizenship, indicating that the ceremony should be held in a solemn atmosphere in front of the state coat of arms and the flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Interior Ministry.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place - the list of places where the russian coat of arms can be placed is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, offices of heads of state bodies, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive authorities, etc.
Most likely, it could be registry offices.
Those wishing to obtain Russian citizenship will make a solemn oath after the officials check their documents.
But a Russian passport will be obtained only after he takes the oath, it follows from the revised text.
A week ago, the draft stated that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that Russia will be sworn in from the age of 18, not from 14.
There is a rule that incapacitated or limited able-bodied persons will be released from swearing, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or sign the oath themselves.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt from this procedure and "other persons"
Also, the updated bill spells out a special procedure for admission to Russian citizens of Ukrainians who are considered native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to officially renounce Ukrainian citizenship, having submitted the relevant application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the statement will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
The renunciation of "foreign" citizenship, as now, would not be required if it was provided for by an international treaty or if it was not possible "for reasons beyond the control of the individual".
A group of deputies, including the first vice-speaker of the DG Ivan Melnikov (CPRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ayrat Farrahov (all - "United Russia") proposed the relevant amendment to the law.
I think many of you know that it is impossible to get a certificate from Ukraine.
Accordingly, a lot of people are waiting for a decision on their fate on the citizenship of the Russian Federation, - explained the head of the Duma Committee on State Construction and Law Pavel Krasheninnikov (EP).
In addition, the text made it clear that restrictions on the occupation of certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who have given up their "other" citizenship in writing and surrendered their former passport to the Russian Interior Ministry, but "for reasons beyond his control" he has not ceased to be considered a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are forbidden to hold positions in the municipal service, to be hired on facilities and in organizations whose activities are related to the security of Russia.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or residence permit of another country cannot become a member of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should come into force on September 1, 2017, by which time the necessary by-laws should be ready.
