Judges are offered to protect from the presidents
The Presidential Human Rights Council (HRC) on behalf of Vladimir Putin has drafted proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
HRC proposes to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts and to introduce their electability.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in Russia.
The Supreme Court must also submit its proposals as part of the presidential order.
HRC has finalized proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by the HRC on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the president gave after a meeting with council members.
At the meeting with the members of the council on December 8, 2016, separate cases of judicial arbitrariness were discussed, as well as problems of public control in the places of detention of citizens (see "Y" of December 9).
The HRC's work resulted in 25 proposals, which dealt both with the independence of judges and the identification of judicial errors, as well as funding for courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to increase the independence of the rest of the judges.
If a candidate for the position of a judge successfully passed the contest and received the support of the judicial community, the chairman of the court, in the opinion of the HRC, should submit it to the appointment, not having the right to refuse, as the law allows now.
It is also proposed to deprive the President of the right to refer cases to judges.
Do this, experts admit, can specially written computer program.
The HRC also considers that the chairman has no right to "prejudge the results of the qualification of the judge, initiate his bringing to disciplinary responsibility, make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments."
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to "elect the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and "to empower them for a relatively short period with mandatory rotation".
Now all the presidents of the courts (from the republican to the district) are appointed for six years by the president on the recommendation of the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, HRC proposes to re-organize appeals and appeals in the courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in Russia.
The HRC says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation, not at the level of regional courts in the subjects of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts."
Experts take the practice of arbitration courts as the basis.
They have "judicial districts" that do not coincide with the administrative division in Russia, but guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who are hampered by the use of "telephone law."
Hrc's magistrates propose to strengthen the people's jurors to consider some "categories of civil and administrative cases" with their participation.
For example, the deprivation of parental rights, the reinstatement at work, the protection of honor and dignity, the deprivation of a driver's license, etc.
"These are only our proposals," explained Tamara Morshchakova, a retired member of the HRC and a judge of the Constitutional Court.
She also recalled that the President's order applied not only to the HRC, but also to the Supreme Court ,VS), which had not yet disclosed its proposals.
The Armed Forces (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Commissioner for Human Rights in Russia) still have time to carry out the assignment.
The Chairman of the Armed Forces Vyacheslav Lebedev has until September 1 to report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in Russia.
Living a high life: Semi-storey and cunning design tricks have turned this small apartment in Earls Court into a spacious dwelling
Joan Lee, a former real estate banker, moved from a spacious home in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the ground floor of a pretty model house in the style of queen Anne, and in favor of the new design says that Joan did not pack her things and did not move again.
"I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge in a much larger area," says Joan.
"I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and there were the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered a price on the same day."
Since first viewing, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
Originally it was a one-bedroom apartment - you had to go through the kitchen to get into the bedroom - and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a semi-floor to squeeze maximum use out of the generous height of the ceilings.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands," she says.
To that end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the Notting Hill architectural and design studio Duck and Shed to use the 12.5-foot-tall ceilings and create a dwelling that would not only be a successful project, but would be suitable for Joan's life.
The ceiling was not high enough to arrange two rooms one above the other, so the architectural task was to create a semi-floor, where you could stand in full height.
Erfan had to think creatively to cope with the brief.
"Working with steel structures is very difficult," he explains.
"We had to position the rooms so that they were one above the other, and we didn't have to bend.
It was necessary not just to build a simple platform, but so bend the structures, so that they were at the right height and allowed to use the rooms from above and below."
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-size rooms one above the other in the all-out space - and many more interesting things.
Retrouvius overlooks the chic living room below.
Mirror furniture with a golden finish, silver accents and vintage lighting devices from Serge Mooy set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in the addition of entertainment, space and light.
The short corridor is framed by mirrors to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, the mirrored security panel appears to be a window to another room.
At the entrance, mirrored cabinets serve to store all of Joan's utensils.
To create a sense of a more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can block the kitchen when it is not used.
The folding kitchens are nothing new.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a moving up door, like in a garage.
"Engineering was involved here," Erfan said of the steel-reinforced wood-fiber shield door.
"It's equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily."
Thanks to the judicious use of space and storage space, Joan received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom and an improved layout.
"At the end of the day, floor space is exactly what you're going to sell, that is, what your property is valued for," Erfan says.
"Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on the floor area."
Here they were able to increase the floor area, using high-quality materials that give the space a tinge of luxury.
"Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection with the house," Erfan says.
"No one falls in love with wiring in the walls.
It is important, but it does not touch the strings of our hearts."
This is an indication that due to good design and increased meterage, the apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you may decide to stay.
