The money was invested in real estate, and the List of De Lutis family properties now includes office buildings, plots for development in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and in Mount Buller and shopping centres in the suburbs.
Under an agreement with his late father, Colin - whom Paul describes as the "main driving force and dominant personality" of the De Lutis family - owns about two-thirds of the company's assets, and Paul owns about one-third.
According to court records, this means That Colin's property is 316 million and Paul's is 176 million.
The division of property and money became a stumbling block for Paul.
"The section proposed by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best parts of the property," he wrote in his first testimony in 2015.
The first Supreme Court hearings were held last Friday after several failed reconciliation attempts.
The brothers are now arguing over who will control the existing business - from which, according to Paul, Colin ruled him out.
Colin claims that this is not the case, but accuses Paul of mismanagement of some objects.
In testimony given by Colin at the beginning of the trial, he says he hopes to resolve the dispute.
"My Italian roots make me consider the family a top priority," he wrote.
Court costs are rising like a snowball: hundreds of pages of testimony, emails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer have been added to the case; Both parties have attracted some of the most prominent lawyers, including the royal lawyer Allan Myers, and the best concoctions.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late husband Luigi were immigrants from Italy; They ran dairy bars and delis in the late 1950s, and in the early 1970s bought a shop in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood, where Colin opened the first family-run jeans store.
Colin says he started Westco when he was "in the last grade of school, and Paul was then a boy (about 10 years old)."
Anna De Lutis says she and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to hand over their possessions to their sons without conflict.
"Luigi often told me that he didn't want the brothers to go to court," she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutis group of companies; Colin says Mark got $10 million when he went out of business, and Luke got $26 million.
