Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the AFL club's board of directors and, according to a 2015 biography published by Eddie McGuire, the TV star's best friend.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin responded by texting, saying that since the case had not yet been tried in court, "I really have nothing to say."
"I am very, very sorry that my brother Paul has decided to sue me and to put our family's name in court," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in testimony that he was trying to meet his brother's demands.
"Our father wouldn't want to see Paul and I arguing in court," he said, adding that he "still hopes for a resolution of the conflict."
That hope seemed to dissipate on Friday.
"The decision in our case will soon be handed down by the court," Colin wrote.
Trump's new chief of staff plans to limit the president's access.
Others tried to do so and were defeated.
Maybe John F. Kelly will really succeed.
In that case, he'll be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information coming to President Trump, including news reports from the media - hoping to keep the chief in a calmer state.
That's what reporter Josh Dawie says.
"At a meeting held by the new White House chief of staff, John F. Kelly, with his chief of staff on his first day in office, he identified a major issue in the White House under President Donald Trump that he hopes to address: poor channels of information to the president."
Kelly told staff that information should go through it - in paper form or through briefings - because the president would be better off making decisions if he got the right information.
Kelly's diagnosis is perfectly correct, but others have already failed in trying to subdue Trump by tracking his information.
President Trump's relationship with television began decades ago - and now that he's in the White House, his habit of watching TV is still strong.
"When Trump, as a candidate, resented the unfair coverage of the campaign, it was helpful to show him that he was getting fair coverage in publications that could be persuaded," Sam Nanberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri wrote in Politico at the time that "according to six former members of the campaign, in order to keep in check Trump's habit of writing on Twitter, it was necessary to make sure that there was a constant stream of praise in the information he received personally."
Ok.
But the idea that Trump's habit of tweeting on Twitter has ever been "under control" is ridiculous.
Maybe these members of the campaign know something we don't know - for example, that if it weren't for them, Trump's tweets would have been even more provocative.
We may never know about tweets that Trump didn't post.
If his staff kept him out of trouble at least a few times, their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has ever managed to keep Trump from adding fuel to the fire.
Part of the problem is that in a White House divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to advance their agenda by giving Trump material - reliable or not - that confirms their views.
Politico - just in time for this story - wrote in May about the tendency of advisers to constantly shove the president questionable information.
Here's one example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"Current and former Trump staffers say that Trump can respond very harshly to negative press reports, especially those containing dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds out who was behind them.
That's what happened in late February, when someone slipped the president a printout of an article from GotNews.com, the website of Internet provocateur Charles K. Johnson, in which Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Welsh was accused of "standing behind a series of leaks" in the White House.
It doesn't matter that Johnson is forever banned on Twitter for aggressive behavior, that he didn't provide specific facts or that in the past he ran false accusations and then denied them.
Trump read the article and started asking staff about Welsh."
Goldmacher adds that then-Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and Secretary of Staff Rob Porter "tried to build a system to manage and document the flow of papers that Trump receives."
How did it work?
Three months later, Kelly is trying to do the same.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump still has an impulsive nature, and his aides are still fighting each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly's task very difficult.
Tyumen prosecutor's office fights HIV dissident
The prosecutor's office challenged the ruling of the Kalinin District Court of Tyumen, which terminated the criminal case against a local woman whose young daughter died of HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died because the mother was hiv dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court absolved her of responsibility in connection with her reconciliation with her father.
The Prosecutor's Office believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished in order not to set a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against a resident of Tyumen was initiated under Article 109 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (causing death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died from HIV infection 4In stage.
According to the prosecutor's office, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
"The woman was not treated herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV infection does not exist," the prosecutor's office of the Tyumen region explained.
The criminal case was submitted to the Kalinin district court of Tyumen, which on July 25 decided to stop it.
The petition was filed by the father of the deceased girl, explaining that he "forgave his wife, has no complaints against her, she made amends and apologized".
The Prosecutor's Office disagreed with the court's decision and appealed, demanding that the order to dismiss the case be overturned and sent to a new hearing.
The girl died, and it is impossible to make amends for the harm caused by the crime.
The HIV-infected mother, contrary to the recommendations of doctors, refused to examine the baby and treat her for a dangerous infection," the press service of the prosecutor's office said.
According to the supervisory body, she should be punished, otherwise her example will be followed by other HIV dissidents.
According to the Tyumen AIDS Center, there are now about 12 children with HIV in the Tyumen region who do not receive medical care because of their parents' refusal.
"And this situation has already improved - during the year of work of the special group half of parents who categorically refused to treat children from HIV, changed their minds - allowed to make a diagnosis, began to take drugs," - said spokeswoman of the AIDS Center Elena Loseva.
According to her, it is impossible to influence parents by legislative means, and as a result not all HIV-infected children can be detected - mothers do not allow them to be examined, hide, run away with children from hospitals.
What are the dangers of HIV dissidents?
Late last year, St. Petersburg sociologists presented the results of Russia's first study of the so-called HIV dissident movement.
HIV dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Doctors and activists of AIDS-service NGOs call such views anti-medical, and in their spread see a serious threat.
