Italy is tightening its tone on NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs that own rescue vessels in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue their work unless they comply with new rules governing their activities.
"If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities," Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turin daily Stampa.
Minniti's warning came a day after Italian authorities confiscated a vessel belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which had only been working for a year, declined to comment on the merits of the detailed charges brought against it by the Italian prosecutor Ambrojo Cartosio.
"For us, saving human life is and will remain a top priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue our activities in the search and rescue zone now," the organization said in a statement on social media.
"We will be able to assess all the charges made now only after we have gathered all the information and been able to assess the situation."
Italian authorities have been monitoring the ship Juventa, owned by Jugend Rettet, since October.
Its crew is suspected of taking whole lifeboats on board migrants who were sent directly to them by traffickers and allowing smugglers to leave with boats that they could use again.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles off the Libyan coast, according to the prosecution, which was published in Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the instructions of the Italian coastguard authorities, who control rescue operations in the area, more out of humanitarian zeal than for any other reason.
The Code of Conduct assumes, mainly, that Juventa-type vessels will have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to obey the code: Save the Children, Maltese MOAS and Pro-Activa Open Arms from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that it believed the new rules were unnecessary but acceptable, provided they did not cause any "meaningful changes or interference" to its rescue operations.
