"In Libya, we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict"
The Russian authorities have recently significantly increased their policy on the Libyan direction, and delegations of the warring Libyan parties have become involved with visits to Moscow.
The head of the Russian contact group on the intra-Libyan settlement at the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma, assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic Lev Degov told "Y" what goals Moscow pursues in the region and who is betting.
Almost nothing is known about the contact group on Libya, which you head.
Here, let's say, the contact group on Ukraine - everyone knows about it.
And here is the veil of mystery.
What exactly do you do, what are your goals?
The contact group was created at the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are overseen by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (Deputy of the Duma from Chechnya.
The latter is authorized to work on the Libyan direction by the speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the creation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker "Mechanic Chebotarev" (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board. - "Y").
We thought about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group of military specialists, representatives of the State Duma was created, our work was supported by the head of Chechnya Ramzan Kadyrov.
And how did it happen that you were the one who led it?
Since I have been working in Libya since 2008, I was approached with an offer to lead the group.
Our activities were not limited to the release of sailors from chebotarev's Mechanics.
We have been able to establish contacts with representatives of all the main factions opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government led by Faiz Saraj. - "Y") is based, and with Tobruk (the seat of parliament, which opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya.
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Libya's Vice-Premier - "Y"), we were able to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
Then it was decided to make better use of these contacts, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I want to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict, we are engaged in a dialogue with everyone.
How many people are part of the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
Now the contact group consists of five people.
Among them there are people with experience in law enforcement agencies, including the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to introduce representatives of the Institute of the Middle East of the Russian Academy of Sciences as part of the group of specialists in the region.
There are no permanent employees in Libya, and this is not necessary yet.
Are there Russian military advisers and instructors in Libya now?
And if so, which side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All conversations and publications about it are not true.
But your contact group includes the former military...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or cities that have been closed up to a certain point, such as Misrata (where militias that played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and have been noticeably intensified in the following years.
We came to Misrata in January this year.
We were scared, told that there were all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are such rumors, what is the real role of Islamists there.
In Misrata, we met with all the representatives of the groups that were engaged in the destruction of IS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was recaptured from the militants of the banned Islamic State in Russia - "Y").
We wanted to look at them, meet these people, check the information that they played a decisive role in the destruction of IS in Libya, not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed these merits.
And what conclusion did you come to?
Is Islamic State not Haftar defeated in Libya?
He wasn't the one who did it.
Haftar was conducting operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And with IS in Sirte, the government-controlled structures in Tripoli were fighting.
And, by the way, we invited people to Russia who carried out this anti-terrorist operation.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from April 19 to April 23 this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, the Duma, the Foreign Ministry and the Russian Guard.
You, as we understand, are in all Libyan regions and probably imagine the mood of local elites and warlords.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements and elections reached in Paris at the end of July by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj?
Or again, as has happened many times in the past, agreements will be broken, hostilities will resume, the parties will try to seize power alone?
For us, a good signal was the fact that Saraj and Haftar agreed to the next meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, the two leaders have been very negative about each other.
And as for Russia's position...
Often write and say that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe in it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misrata, and Haftar on that day climbed aboard the Russian aircraft carrier "Admiral Kuznetsov".
It was a coincidence.
But in Misrata they did not believe in coincidence.
We were told, "You must be very brave people who came to us today."
But our task is to show that we do not support only Haftar, we are in dialogue with all the key players in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar talked.
Does mutual understanding with Russian partners on a human, emotional level facilitate the fact that he studied twice in the USSR?
And by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
If he knows Russian, he is very concerning.
But the fact that he studied with us, of course, facilitates dialogue with him.
And by the way, it's not just him.
When we talk to the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And now they speak Russian perfectly.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent they are nostalgic for it.
Do you think it is likely that the arms embargo imposed on Libya will be lifted soon?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in Russian arms supplies?
They are interested, of course, but, as I said, we do not take sides in this conflict and do not want to arm some to the detriment of others.
We would like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, there are constant calls from the Libyans that Russia somehow contribute to its removal.
The process of drafting a constitution is now actively progressing in Libya.
We hope that the parties will reach compromise solutions and achieve internal consensus.
Then the elections should be held, as mentioned at the meeting of Saraj and Haftar.
If the elections are held and the legitimate government is finally elected (and now neither side has such status), it is possible to put the issue of lifting the arms embargo in the UN Security Council.
It is pointless and dangerous to raise this issue now, but it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
Recently, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees sailing from Libya, feels abandoned to the fate of allies from the EU.
Can Moscow help its Italian partners in this situation by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is Haftar's group of troops to take control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers smuggling immigrants to Europe?
It's a very timely question.
We are actively working on it.
The Italians need Russia's support because Moscow is engaged in dialogue with Haftar, Saraj, Misrata and the south of the country.
And in this matter the tribes in southern Libya play a big role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about southerners stopping the flow of migrants on distant approaches?
So, conventionally speaking, were the buses carrying Nigerian migrants going back?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these streams going.
We hope to help unite the southerners in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes in the south.
But first, we would like to see unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The head of the government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered an Islamist who is a supporter of the introduction of Sharia law in the country.
How radical is he?
Wouldn't that be an obstacle in building relations with Russia or the West?
I'll give you my personal opinion of him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But there are Islamists in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya should be a perfectly normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
And it is also actively fighting terrorists.
Where does he get that reputation?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, where there is a legislative, executive and judicial branch.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other state structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in us not getting there.
And we mixed all the cards for them and began to actively communicate with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the benefits of this work: Rosneft has entered into a cooperation agreement with Libya's state oil company, NOC.
NOC Director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Rosneft's head Igor Sechin struck a deal, is himself from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I suppose it's reselling.
And what are Russia's economic interests in Libya?
Plans to re-sign contracts signed under Muammar Gaddafi.
These include previous agreements in the transport sector (railway construction), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do Libyans have anything to pay?
Well, they have oil.
So, as in the case of Iran, we are talking about the oil-for-services scheme?
I don't know what the scheme will be, I don't deal with these issues directly.
In fact, the economy is not the main thing for Russia in Libya.
We are there, in fact, engaged in peacekeeping work.
The main thing for us is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans to agree among themselves so that they can establish order and Libya ceases to be a conducive environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task - to help the Libyan people and squeeze out terrorists.
Do you have any data on the presence in Libya (now or earlier) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out this.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that to date no natives from Russia and other countries of the former Soviet Union are not there.
He said that he had about 50,000 phone records of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya. - "Y") and that the Russian speech did not sound there.
And from which states are these militants then?
I don't want to go into that detail.
Then let's formulate the question differently.
How many Islamist militants are Libyans in Libya?
There are almost no Libyans among them, there are no more than 5%.
The rest are newcomers.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks following the example of Paris?
There are such plans.
We are holding active negotiations with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have declared their readiness to come to Moscow or Grozny.
And when can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say right now.
Several more visits are to take place, and then I hope that there will be clarity about the time and place of the negotiations.
