Michelle Carter's sentencing for reports that prompted Conrad Roy's suicide
A Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for using text messages and phone calls to incite the suicide of her boyfriend Conrad Roy.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will have to serve 15 months behind bars and another five years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father told the hearing on Thursday: "My family is heartbroken.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was allowed to remain at large pending an appeal.
She faced a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict standing, clenching her arms and lowering his eyes.
"She killed Conrad Roy by her actions," the prosecutor told the court.
She interrupted his life to improve his.
She pleaded not guilty," she said.
"She showed no remorse."
But Carter's lawyer said it was a "tragic case that she deeply regrets."
But Judge Lawrence Monis said he believed her "age, maturity level or even mental illness did not significantly affect her actions."
The prosecutor read out a statement from Roy's mother Lynn Roy, which read: "Not a single day has passed when I would not have mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I'm coping - I try to support his sisters despite all the pain that will stay with us forever," it reads.
Roy's sister Kamdin Roy said she was relentlessly haunted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
"To lose a person who has always been with me since I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life," she said.
This case is likely to set a legal precedent, since there is no law in Massachusetts that would provide for the responsibility of advising a person to commit suicide.
Carter was 17 when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning in 2014.
The case caught the attention of the entire country when it became known that he was pushed to commit suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself, I don't know there are many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death while he was vacationing with his family.
Minutes before the suicide, she wrote, "You have to do this, Conrad" and "You just have to turn on the ignition, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monis said Carter wanted attention through Roy's death and forbade her from talking to the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
Lawyers' opinions on this issue were divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British flatmate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
Knox, 30, posted a dissenting opinion in the Los Angeles Times, saying, "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
