Climate change threatens lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and Southern France, but there are now fears that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavender has become worse to grow due to dry weather and disease-carrying insects; this has caused a constant headache for scientists and farmers who are trying to find a solution.
Erik Shes, an expert at the Provence-based agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM, says: "Lavender in Provence is indeed under threat because in recent years this plant has been affected by climate change: in spring and especially in autumn, there has been much less rain.
This affects the lifespan of lavender.
And then there are the little cicadas that jump on the leaves of insects that carry micro-bacteria; There are a lot of them in very dry weather."
There is a lot at stake.
