The murder of a journalist underscores that it is becoming increasingly dangerous in Mexico.
Employees of the weekly newspaper Riodos usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to cover the latest violent crimes in the state of Sinaloa, linked to organized crime, corrupt officials or the ongoing war of drug traffickers.
But today, overwhelmed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about security.
They were told they had to change their habits.
Two senior journalists discussed what seemed safer: taking the children with them to the office where a grenade was thrown in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three words on the board hanging in the room: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column - no evidence is needed, suspicions and internal feelings will suffice.
These are drug dealers, politicians, businessmen, journalists, who are suspected of being in the custody of the government or cartels, a whole list of scoundrels, which make the work of covering the chaos in Mexico dangerous.
Violence does not provide respite, and there are more and more journalists among the corpses that are multiplying in the country: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, at least 25 since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and this year, at least seven people have died in seven states.
Among the latter - their publisher and mastermind, co-founder of "Riodos" Javier Valdez Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist," Valdez wrote in one of his many books on violent drug crimes.
His absence is felt very keenly, although his presence is ubiquitous - a large photograph of Valdez showing the middle finger, with the inscription "Justice" hanging on the facade of the Building "Riodos"; Two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts depicting his smile, face in glasses or his signature Panama.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; journalists discuss their common trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although in 2010 the office of a special federal prosecutor was organized to investigate journalistic cases, so far, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, only two cases have been investigated.
As with most of the thousands of drug-trafficking and organized crime murders each year, the killers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
Riodos journalists insist that they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, although they are heartbroken, although it is much more dangerous around them now.
Without information about the killers, without justice from talking about security at meetings, it is of little use, Ibarra said.
"It's very foolish to waste time at this seminar," he says.
"Until we know the cause, we suspect everyone."
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the Riodos office in the state capital of Culiacan.
He managed to drive only a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men; he was pulled from the car and shot 12 times, probably because of the newspaper's name - which means "Twelfth River."
The gunman drove off in his car and crashed it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He is survived by his wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually quickly diverge on Culiacan.
But about Valdez almost everyone is silent.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the U.S. last January, Sinaloa has become one of the bloodiest battlegrounds in the country as rival factions struggle to fill the vacuum.
Let's not say that one or more people are killed every day on the streets of Sinaloa, or that the cemetery is filled with decorated two-story mausoleums of drug-ships, which are larger than the homes of many living people.
Forget for a moment that the state of "calm" is just when one of the cartels takes control of the seaside state with important ports and drug trafficking routes leading to the United States.
Despite this and the fact that Valdez was well aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bohorquez, the 60-year-old co-founder and director of Riodos, is crushed by guilt for not being able to protect a friend.
He thinks two mistakes helped the murder.
First, an interview with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the cartel's rival factions that is at war with Guzman's sons, was published in February.
The publication could infuriate the sons; people believed to be gang members bought up all copies of the publication as soon as they were delivered to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he did not force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper that wrote about the same story was seized.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had been walking away from danger for so long, his friends and colleagues thought he would always be.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroest and in 2003, together with five colleagues, founded Riodos, selling his 50-dollar shares.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to engage in journalism without dealing with the topic of drugs," Bohorquez said.
Over time, the newspaper has earned a reputation as a bold and honest publication, sales and advertising revenues grew.
Journalists liked that they could publish bold reports without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted that in this edition they could read about something that no one else dared to write about.
Eight years after its founding, Riodos won the prestigious Maria Moores Cabo Award for reporting in Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award for his courage in investigating Mexico's drug trade, wherever it was.
He openly confessed that he was scared.
"I want to move on with my life," he said at the CPJ Awards.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is "a way of life," he said last October in an interview with Rompuyento TV.
"You have to accept the tasks that fall on you as a journalist - either like that or you just fool around."
I don't want to be asked, "What did you do when there were so many deaths around... why didn't you say what was going on?"
The Riodos staff miss Valdez, a prankster who swore like a loader in the port, a friend generous to hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to get together.
They relied on the order they had in place.
He should always wear his hat.
He had to go to El Guayaba, the bar across from the office, and always sit there at the same table.
Now they ask: was he ruined by the love of one-time routine?
His death also led them to question their calculations of how best to do their job and stay alive.
"They don't like it when you know their wives, their children, their legal business and underground drug-trafficking airfields.
"These things were over the line," Bohorquez said.
The result, even at the best of times, was a high level of self-censorship and the desire for self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
Stay away from what smells bad.
The problem, says Riodos editor Andres Villarreal, is that "the sense of smell can be deceived... and then what happened to Javier happens."
The old rules, he says, no longer apply in Sinaloa - as in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states where there is a poisonous mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak government institutions and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In the room where the employees of "Riodos" gathered for security training, suddenly it was forbidden to bring cell phones: a few days before it became known that spyware, which are sold exclusively to governments, are used in Mexico to spy on journalists and public activists.
Outside, two police officers take shelter in the shade of a tree from the 104-degree heat (40 degrees Celsius).
They were tasked by the state government to guard the Riodos office, which is located in a four-story building in the bourgeois neighborhood of Culiacan.
Some journalists were half-jokingly asked if the police were among the 50 per cent of the officers on whom the Governor himself had said they could not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists went to a mountainous area, which is de facto controlled by drug gangs.
In the next issue "Riodos" counted on three main themes.
This is the murder in Sinaloa of the brother of former boxing champion Julio Cesar Chavez.
They also had exposed government spending concentrated in the governor's hometown.
And there was a group kidnapping at one of Culiacan's most expensive restaurants, a block from the prosecutor's office.
It was not officially announced who had been kidnapped or how it happened, so it was necessary to be careful when it came time to write about what everyone in the city knew: that it was a favorite restaurant at the same time drug dealers and authorities.
One of their journalists learned from open databases that the restaurant was registered in the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which had dominated all levels of government for most of the past century.
Recently, several PRI governors have been charged with high-profile corruption.
Villarreal asked reporters to write about previous incidents at the restaurant, including when Guzman's son "El Chapo" eluded the military.
Until a few months ago, readers would have been looking for Valdez's column with the most reliable information about the kidnapping.
"We would have known what had happened before," said Villarreal, 46, dubbed "El Flaco" for his lean physique.
"Today, all channels of communication with our sources have been severed."
Valdez's office is now used as a warehouse for posters and stickers to protest the killings of journalists because employees have become something they never thought they would become: activists acting on behalf of the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez took several posters and went the next morning to a demonstration at the local prosecutor's office dedicated to another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in the state of Michoacan in the west of the country three days after Valdez was killed.
The burned body was found, and the authorities said it was him, based on DNA tests.
Across the country, journalists began to speak out louder, organize protests and write "SOS Press" on the sidewalks and walls of houses.
On that day, Director Bohorquez was in Washington trying to gain international support in demanding justice in the Valdez case.
In a meeting with the Governor of Sinaloa the day after Valdez's murder, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their killings for telling the truth.
She then asked not to be given more job coverage of government activities, fearing that anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdez has said many times that journalists in Mexico are "surrounded" by organized crime, its accomplices in the government and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Drug Journalism, he wrote that reporters are not just drug gangs killed; they do so on the orders of politicians and security services who are in cahoots with organized crime.
The Press Protection Committee ,Artikulo 19 estimates that half of the attacks on journalists last year were ordered by police and government officials.
"In Mexico, you die because they want to shut you up," Ramirez said.
Of course, murder scares people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elisabeth Macias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
A note was found on her body, presumably written on behalf of the zetas cartel: "I am here because of my articles".
A computer keyboard and headphones lay next to her severed head.
Some publications chose to close as the newspaper El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua after its correspondent Miroslava Britch was killed in March.
Others continue to hold on, like "El Magnana" from Nuevo Laredo after the assassination of its leader in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juarez publicly addressed drug cartels through a front-page editorial entitled "What do you want from us?"
Some journalists have left their home states or even the country.
It's an excruciating decision.
It is difficult to find work in exile and they are still in danger in the streets.
And sometimes they get killed, as is apparently the case with photographer Ruben Espinoza, who was killed in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who remain and continue to work balance risky decisions on a daily basis.
Ibarra - who once dreamed of being a poet - admits he is scared to write about the drug trade.
"Mexico is going to hell, and that's why I became a journalist," he says.
Last Friday, at midnight, when the last issue was ready for printing, the publishers of "Riodos" were sitting on the sidewalk next to the office and drinking beer when suddenly their phones rang simultaneously.
A series of skirmishes between rival gangs and security forces near the resort town of Mazatlan left behind, according to confirmed, 19 bodies.
The war continued to flare up, as promised in a series of messages from cartels found in the area.
Sitting on the sidewalk, they posted the news on the Riodos website via a mobile phone.
The next day we had to redo the first page.
Nearby sirens erupted - another firefight in the vicinity.
Bohorquez looked ready for the defense of the police officers guarding them.
If they were scared, they didn't show it.
Sitting under a huge portrait of the deceased founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was on display throughout Sinaloa, the Riodos staff continued his case.
"How can you think about closing," Bohorquez said, "if on the very day Javier was killed, the intern asked me to send her outside to do a report?"
Dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it seems to be a statue, though terrifying.
Researchers said the first found remains of an incredible rhino-sized creature discovered by a Canadian miner have survived so well that experts have named it the "Mona Lisa among dinosaurs."
It was so well preserved that they were even able to determine that the color of his scaly skin was reddish-brown - and to say that he had, in a way, a "dark past."
The report, published in the journal Modern Biology, described it as "the best preserved of The time's finds and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world."
This fossil is a newly found specimen of nodosaurus that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
His incredible good fortune stunned the researchers, who call him "really wonderful."
This herbivorous thyrophor is the best preserved fossil of its kind in the history of the finds, according to articles in the journal National Geographic.
He was found by Sean Funk while working at the Suncor Millennium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He came across something that seemed to be different from the surrounding breed, and decided to look more closely.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
For the next six years, work was carried out to locate the animal inside an earthen block weighing 2,500 feet (1,100 kilograms).
Now that all this hard work has been done, the finished result can be demonstrated.
"You just have to squint a little bit, and you can almost believe that he's asleep," said lead author Caleb Brown, a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum, where the creation is being showcased.
"He will enter the history of science as one of the most beautiful and well-preserved specimens of dinosaurs - the Mona Lisa among dinosaurs."
By studying its skin, the researchers found that it was herbivorous, despite the fact that it was covered with a shell and resembled a walking tank, apparently exposed to significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This shell-covered dinosaur used red-and-white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as protective coloring, which is also used by many animals of our day.
This would allow him to merge quickly with the environment and avoid meeting enemies, experts say, suggesting he was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
The 110 million-year-old creature, a family of nodosaurs, was widely published in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
Scientists have already studied the animal and gave it the name Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of museum laboratory technician Mark Mitchell, one of the members of the group who spent more than 7,000 hours during its painstaking excavation.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international group of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and shell plates on his body.
They found a protective coloration, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although protective coloration is well-extended, the discovery came as a surprise because the size of the Borealopelta dinosaur is much larger than the size of living animals with protective coloration.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred to mask confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with protective colors - such as deer, zebras or armadillos - are much smaller and are more accessible prey, indicating that nodosaurus had to seriously fight for survival.
"The serious threat from predators to a massive, shell-covered dinosaur shows just how dangerous the Cretaceous Dinosaurs were," Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in dinosaur scales also suggests that its skin was to be reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about its life, including the preserved contents of its digestive tract, to find out what it ate during his last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was carried away into the sea, where it sank and with its back down lay on the bottom of the ocean.
In those days, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and rivers and oceans were likely to spread much further inland than they do now.
"This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, and at the same time is completely preserved in three dimensions, preserving the original shape of the animal," Brown said.
"As a result, the animal now looks almost the same as it looked then, in the Early Cretaceous period.
You don't have to use imagination to recreate it, you just have to squint a little, and you can almost believe that he's asleep."
The Cretaceous period is an era when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of them, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, the tyrophor could be hunted by someone from his formidable ancestors.
They include Acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot (11.5-meter) monster weighing six tons.
The scientists, whose latest findings are published in the journal Modern Biology, believe that Borealopelta was carried away at sea after his death and mummified in the ila.
