According to the museum staff, it is the best preserved tyreophore in the world, along with the skin and shell, and it is intact, from the muzzle to the femurs.
On average, these creatures were approximately 18 feet (five meters) long and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was the twenty-20m thorns protruding from the shoulders.
Researchers believe that this herbivorous thyrophorus was hard to walk on what is now Canada, until the spilled river took it into the open sea.
But the underwater burial of the dinosaur has preserved its shell with precision to the smallest detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remnants of the skin still cover the bumpy shell plates along the dinosaur skull.
As Michel Greshko wrote in an article for National Geographic magazine, such a degree of preservation is "rare as winning a lottery."
The longer I look at him, the more striking he seems.
Fossilized skin residues still cover the bumpy shell plates that dot the animal's skull.
