Similarities: The artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the center of the hall at the Friedman Gallery in New York, people's faces hang from the ceiling on the wire - white, black and brown, all somehow elusively similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harging from swabs from the cheek and hair trims sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the cuts from Fort Levenworth prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for famously sending confidential diplomatic cables to WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which was launched on August 2, is 10 per.50.
It's the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey Harbor, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and a famous dissident, whom Barack Obama commuted just three days before the end of his presidency.
After analyzing Manning's computer-generated DNA program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of faces that could be in people with such a genome, Dewey-Harging created a deep, though difficult-to-perceive manifesto, dedicated not only to the plasticity of DNA data - the different ways of interpreting them and the inerent determinism of these interpretations - but also the perception of identity.
Manning, who was born with the name Bradley Edward but has been outspoken since her teens, said she considers herself a woman, was sentenced in 2013 to 20 counts, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her photos in prison were unavailable, so only one photo of her was known: a grainy black-and-white selfie in which Manning, in a platinum-hued wig, clearly feeling uncomfortable, was sitting behind the wheel of a car; she was associated with this photograph.
In 2015, Dewey Harbor successfully completed its 2012 project Visions of Strangers.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, singling out DNA from the debris and creating images of what these people might look like.
And then she got an email from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article," Dewey-Hagborg explained at a preview of the new press exhibition.
At the time, Chelsea was not allowed to visit or take pictures, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted to get a portrait made from her DNA.
In such an unusual way, the artist and her prison-sitting muse became pen pals and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book, "Suppressed Images," illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which depicted how in the future the president would commute Chelsea's punishment and be able to attend the exhibition in person.
The fact that Obama really decided to release Manning just days after the book was published was a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a military prison in Kansas.
There's something profound and powerful about the fact that the exhibition is opening right now that Donald Trump is declaring war on people who disclose classified information in government and inventing new ways to incite twitter the animosity he's meant to mitigate.
When Dewey Harbor was asked about the coincidence of this whole in time, she said that "accidentally nothing happens."
In a statement from the artist, written on the wall of the gallery, Manning's huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of a point over the "i" in her surname) calls for an end to "automatic division based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture."
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar made of pencil C, G and A.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist scientifically puts it), Dewey-Harug hoped to show how amazingly similar we all are, at least in their biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome doesn't define what we are, how open the genetic data is to interpretation, and how subjective it is," Dewey-Harug said. her 2007 video work "False Memories" is also on display here.
"These DNA can tell us so many different stories, and 30 of these stories are here."
The last part of the exhibition, which was possible in one room, is the above-mentioned novel in the comics.
On it, Manning in the style of King Kong appears above the building of the Correctional Barracks of the United States with a loudspeaker in his hand.
"If they kill your speech, they will win," it reads.
"So never shut up."
"It's a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me," says the artist, who greets us from Philadelphia.
"I still have goosebumps when I talk about it."
Manning has not yet seen the exhibition in person - as it was visionaryly depicted in the comics - but when she comes, she will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacrums gathered like crowds of protesters.
This is also done intentionally, as well as all in the exhibition up to the height (5"2, manning's height), on which the genetic haplogroups were drawn with a pencil.
"I used to hang them on the walls, but now I want them to look like a crowd of people," Dewey-Hargg says of the portraits.
"I wanted them to be like the mass movement that formed around Chelsea as a movement that stood behind its liberation."
