Russian Deputy Prime Minister Mutko: "We will meet the requirements of the WADA roadmap in the near future"
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vitaly Mutko said the world Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) conditions set for the reopening of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA) would be met soon.
"A certain stage in compliance has been passed, RUSADA has received the right to plan and conduct tests in conjunction with UKAD (UK Anti-Doping Agency).
The WADA roadmap has been updated accordingly," Mutko said on Thursday.
The Prime Minister commented on the second part of wada's roadmap for restoring compliance with the Code, which lists the terms of RUSADA's reopening and was recently published on the organization's website.
According to Mutko, it does not contain anything that could present difficulties for Russia.
"Everything has been announced, everything will be fulfilled.
And the results will be presented to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future," he added.
However, one of the requirements on the list implies that Russian andi-doping agencies must publicly acknowledge the results of an investigation commissioned by WADA by Canadian lawyer Richard McLaren, which claimed that doping in Russian sport was controlled by the state.
Referring to this issue, Mutko said: "We are investigating because our anti-doping system has failed.
All measures have been taken.
But there were no state programs, and we will not recognize what did not happen."
Mutko echoed the words of Vitaly Smirnov, head of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
In an interview with Russian newspaper Rsport later that day, Smirnov acknowledged the problems in Russian anti-doping structures, but added: "We have repeatedly said that the report contains certain controversial positions and positions.
No one is going to accept this report unconditionally," Smirnov added.
WADA suspended RUSADA from doping control in November 2015 following a doping scandal.
However, in June this year he was allowed to plan and coordinate testing under the supervision of international experts and the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
After visiting the organization's Moscow office in July, WADA Director General Olivier Niggli said RUSADA was "moving in the right direction" to rebuild its work.
