Startups to help your company not become the next "Uber"
Aimee Errett wanted to gauge the level of satisfaction among her startup's e-commerce employees, but the surveys didn't work.
The answers were often vague, useless or, worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
"He's never been consistent or objective," said Errett, who runs a San Francisco-based 75-person company, Madison Reed, an e-commerce company focused on hair care.
So she turned to third parties for help.
Now there is a new kind of startups in the field of work with personnel, which help companies to find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure employee engagement, they allow companies to do rapid surveys, access certain teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass top management and contact the directorate directly.
"Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit to monitor your health, and where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City-based startup Glynd, whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she has gained a better understanding of what her employees think and feel in the three years she has used "Glint."
In addition to the express surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a thermal card of the company and shows in a visual form which departments have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
Companies gradually realize that they need to control the workplace environment, otherwise they will become the next Uber, which was implicated in the scandal, when a former employee published a blog post in which he described an aggressive environment in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For start-ups like Glint, this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for profitable business.
The "Let's Talk About Payment" website, which is dedicated to financial technology, estimates that the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
The Start-up Convercent, based in Denver, Colorado, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid a decline in Uber's reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently appeared among its customers.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customized staff opinion surveys, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous text message hotline that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the directorate.
"The court of public opinion has seized power from the inspectors," said Patrick Kwinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company mistreats employees or behaves unethically, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company could face costly consequences in the form of customer boycotts, employee outflows and lawsuits, mr. Kwinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, has been using Convercent for more than a year to make sure employees are up to date with the rules and procedures, and to offer an easy way to contact the company's head office.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to search for a phone number or head office email, file a formal complaint and hope that she would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, chief legal officer at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company uses the "Convercent" service, problems that used to be hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states - such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay - can be quickly discovered and addressed.
"I can come close to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the employee situation," said Vitrano, who directs the Network's "Ruby Tuesday" risk management team.
"And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees."
According to Mr. Kwinland, companies began to take ethics, values and employee engagement more seriously in 2002, after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron case.
But it was only when "social networks became widespread", that companies realized that they could not keep their dirty laundry from viral distribution on the net.
"Before we started using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for using their products.
It is a business model and an opportunity that has received the approval of venture capitalists who have supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the total capital to $60 million.
This investment is hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that today's employees expect more from their jobs than they did before.
In markets with fierce competition, such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are just a necessary minimum.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and valued, and that they devote their time to companies with a positive mission.
"When people are happy to work for a company, feel they're being heard, and that the work they're doing is working harder, they're more trying to make it a success," said Nina McKuin, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors earn income when companies in their portfolios are doing well; companies do well when employees are dedicated and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it is not surprising that they find support.
According to workplace culture experts, it is important to have data on employee engagement.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can give the impression that change is coming.
And if change does not come quickly enough, or does not occur at all, there may be disappointment, and employees will lose interest.
"If you're going to ask for 4,000 offers, you have to be prepared to have 4,000 conversations," said Russell Rath, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, which has seen companies make mistakes by relying too much on data collection.
"Because if you don't go all the way, the staff will be like, "Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care?"
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports a problem with "Glint."
And, after collecting feedback from employees dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is learning about its employees and hopes that in the long run, this knowledge will help it better retain employees in an industry known for high turnover.
"If you don't try to create a culture of transparency, you lose people," Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose company.
