Bruins team has to practice longer because the National Student Athletic Association cancels workouts twice a day
The time is approaching eleven o'clock in the evening; A crowd of football players from UCLA is delayed to chat on one side of the team's new training fields located on campus.
Some of them pulled off their T-shirts, baring their backs, glistening from sweat after a tense first day of sports camp.
For many of the team's players, these minutes of idleness make up a mid-afternoon break.
Players enrolled in summer classes will head back to the dormitories after a three-hour training session to prepare for the final exams, and the next morning they will return to the Wasserman Football Center for meetings at 6:30 a.m.
Shortly before Monday turned into Tuesday, Bruins coach Jim Mora said, "These guys are going to have a meat grinder for the next three days."
The fact that the National Student Athletic Association canceled workouts twice a day, which was designed to reduce the workload for players, actually lengthened their workday - at least until after the exams on Friday.
That's why the start of the first three training sessions of the UCLA team was scheduled for 7:15 p.m. to fit into an already tight schedule of players.
A side effect of not having two workouts a day has been more days with one workout, and the Bruins are moving the start of camp by nearly a week compared to last year and holding summer school workouts for the first time in Mora's six seasons at Westwood.
According to the schedule, they will have to conduct 18 training sessions until August 20, before starting formal preparations for the first game of the season against the University of Texas team in September.
Mora said he supports a rule change by the National Student Athletic Association, even though he has another point in the players' tight schedule.
"In three or four days we give them this huge load, it's a serious test," Mora said.
'And they just overcame it, they work, they're great guys.
I think when we get to Saturday and we have more time, it's going to be really great."
When camp ends, UCLA will make workouts closed; this is not an easy task, as its fields are in direct sight from the adjacent parking lot and from the nearby Laskin Center, an expensive hotel that has already been bombarded with footballs that overcame the safety net behind the gate.
Bruins players are expected to occupy the hotel starting this weekend, but Mora admits that when the rooms are available during the season, there may be a problem.
"We will have security," Mora said.
"This is a serious problem, and I'm not exaggerating the danger by suggesting that someone can rent a room, sit there and record the training on video.
If you have a video of the workout, it's very serious.
But we'll have security there and security in parking number 8.
We're going to do everything we can with what we have.
I'm not going to worry too much about that.
We have a plan."
