Create a comic novel: One castle in English history
In the recent past, the tiny Castle of Scotney was filmed in the music video "Squeeze" and in the 70s and 80s served as a haven for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy place in the River Beul Valley in Kent, he oversaw the tumultuous history around, and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshireman with a smoky hair and a penchant for historical documents, to a novel-comic.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago," he says enthusiastically.
"You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand."
"Castle in England" covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Eurardian era and tells the story of the families who lived in Scotney; Each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Bryony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book, which is based on archival data: in 2014 he wrote "Dead Man's Teeth and Other Stories" - a collection of documents from the British Library; this project suddenly touched him to the core.
"I could have been touched by a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites," he says.
"It's his fingerprint."
And the letters always smell like smoke, because in those days a fire was lit for lighting.
And 300 years from now, you feel like you're there, too.
Oh, how much I love archives!"
For a man gripped by such a passion for old papers, getting support from the National Trust and the English Art Council and living in a castle for four months ("Honestly, I'm a little stoned there") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days studying the "new" Victorian castle, going through the archives and examining the estate's many treasures and antiques - such as hyena heads on the walls or bottles that had been in the moat for centuries.
He walked through the park and through the ruins of the old castle, talking to foresters, gardeners and sometimes artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
Then at night he "drinked whiskey and sat down to write."
The history of Scotney Castle is not well understood, because the National Trust only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, the staff were just beginning to deal with the archive, which he describes as "what aristocrats have been dumped in the attic for centuries."
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You think land disputes are boring," Rhodes says, "but two families fought for this birch tree.
That's what happens, guys!"
In some of the collection's stories, the castle becomes the starting point for broader explorations in English history: for example, in "The Worker," the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
"There is evidence of a riot that took place in the castle in 1380, in a book called The Knight Families of Kent and Sussex," Rhodes said.
"The peasant uprising started in these places, and I thought that the revolt was a good beginning.
Maybe they were related?"
Other plots are strongly related to the history of the castle - for example, "The Priest", which tells the story of a Jesuit priest, whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "The Smuggler," about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by stuffing the coffin with stones (this was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
Darrells is Rhodes' favorite family of all that the Scotsmen inhabited: "The gentlemen seem to have been a perfect rogue, always getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy older women - I imagine them as a group of nice guys who can look after heiress of big fortunes."
After finishing his work at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elyammyaki - the place where in the early 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it was again overgrown with forest.
But Scotney remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
"I felt something like this: hell, I have to go back to real life."
Fifteen largest banks choose "Russia"
The conflict in the Association of Russian Banks (ARB) is developing: following Sberbank, VTB, VTB-24, Alpha Bank, Gazprombank, Rosselkhozbank, Binbank and Opening FC, seven more credit organizations are going to leave this public organization.
Thus, the organizations that have left the ARB will account for at least 80 percent of the market.
But this is not just an option - all the banks, which announced the break with the ARB, are negotiating with another public organization uniting credit institutions - the Association of Regional Banks "Russia", headed by a well-known politician Anatoly Aksakov, chairman of the State Duma Committee on the Financial Market, recognized, by the way, at the end of the last session and the most effective head of the Duma committee and deputy on the number of drafted bills.
The beginning of the conflict within the ARB was initiated during a discussion in the Federation Council, when the Interregional Banking Council considered new bills, in particular, suggesting a new classification of banks depending on the size of the share capital.
Then Garegin Tosunyan, president of the ARB, said that, in the opinion of the association, this bill is adopted in the interests of the largest banks, which thus try to limit the opportunities of small and medium-sized banks in the regions, intercepting their clientele.
Among other claims there was also criticism against the Central Bank, which, according to Tosunyan, is not always justified in revoking licenses from some banks, which, however, was opposed by the representative of the Central Bank: many heads of fined banks, in particular, Vneshprombank, were members of the governing bodies of the ARB.
Apparently, this exchange of mutually exclusive views in a very sensitive relationship with the main regulator of the banking environment became a visible reason for the fifteen largest banks, stating their disagreement with the policy of the ARB, began to prepare for joining the association "Russia", noting that "the effectiveness of the ARB's work will be low, and constructive dialogue within the banking community is not actually conducted."
Investors will be better off
How will it end?
We will answer immediately the main question, which arises at the slightest failure or conflict in the banking sector or next to it: depositors are not threatened, rather, on the contrary, the reliability of the banking system will increase.
Anatoly Aksakov, known for his meticulousness in everything concerning the interests of banks and their clients, is headed by "Russia" and is highly regarded by the Central Bank: almost all the central bank's management is present at the annual events of the association, and all significant legislative initiatives of the regulator pass through the expert assessments of "regionals".
In terms of personnel and organizational terms, it is obvious that there will also be no particular upheaval.
Undoubtedly, the ARB finds itself in a difficult financial and managerial situation after it loses such powerful and influential participants with their contributions and lobbying capabilities.
However, in this oldest - established in 1991 - an organization that advocates the interests of the banking community, there is considerable potential to continue to improve banking legislation and the field of monetary circulation in general.
