Andrey Otlopkov was transferred from the cosmodrome
As it became known to "Y", the technical director of the Cosmodrome Oriental Andrey Otlopkov started work at the State Space Research and Production Center (GKNPC) named Hrunichev.
Previously, he was de facto engaged in the construction of the Oriental Cosmodrome, but due to disagreements with the management of the Center for the Exploitation of Ground and Space Infrastructure (CENKI) was transferred to the enterprise in Moscow Philae, where he will coordinate production.
Mr. Oklopkov will not have a replacement: the post of technical director is likely to be abolished, and the functionality is scattered on the CENSKI units.
The fact that the technical director of the Eastern and deputy director general of CENKI for technological development Andrei Otlopkov moved to work in the Hrunichev SCNC was told by the top managers of several enterprises of the space industry, as well as an employee of the government apparatus.
"He has been working in his new post for several weeks," - the interlocutors of "Y" in the industry said.
CENKI could not be reached for comment on Thursday, and Mr. Otlopkov himself was unavailable for comment.
However, the information was officially confirmed by the SCNC.
He made a decision to move to the position of director of production coordination, - said the company. - Andrey Otlopkov set a task to provide a launch minimum for the first launch at the Orient Cosmodrome fully fulfilled.
Mr. Otlopkov joined CENCI in 2013, having served in the space forces, particularly in Baikonur, and in Plesetsk- at the "northern" cosmodrome, he served as the first deputy commander in the rank of colonel.
In 2009, Andrei Otlopkov became a defendant in a criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly from his filing regional merchants received state orders for kickbacks, but did not fulfill the commitments made to clean up the separate parts of launch vehicles in the Arkhangelsk region and the Republic of Comey.
He was found not guilty by a jury in 2012.
The responsibilities assigned to him in CENCY for technological development extended to various projects, but the main one was the construction of the cosmodrome in the Far East.
Oleg Ostapenko, the head of the Federal Space Agency, said in an interview with "Yu" that the situation in the East "was critical already in October 2013".
The fact is that a strategic mistake was made in the planning: the completion of construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 launch vehicle were planned at the same time - the end of 2015.
To carry out the launch before the end of the year, they decided to complete the construction six months earlier and the deadline was shifted from December to July 2015.
To speed up the process had to go to the trick: CENKI specialists began to conduct parallel installation of technological equipment at unfinished facilities.
The main supporter of this idea was Andrey Otlopkov.
Despite the existing risks and still the transfer (instead of December 2015," the Soyuz left only on April 28, 2016), this idea paid off, says the source of "Y" at the cosmodrome: "Otherwise, we would not have carried out a single launch from the East, and would have been engaged in construction."
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who oversees the creation of the cosmodrome, jokingly called Andrei Otlopkov his "space Susanin", but it was he who almost always asked for information about the progress of the construction.
I remember Mr. Otlopkov and directness: for example, in an interview with "Y" he proposed to deprive the Federal Agency for Special Construction (Special Construction) of the status of the sole executor in the East and to work directly with subcontractors: "Why should we put all our eggs in one basket of the Special Forces?"
This idea has found support in the government.
Since 2017, CENKI has assumed the duties of general contractor to complete construction and installation work at the launch and technical complex by the planned fourth quarter of the start-ups.
According to Yu, the reason for Mr. Otlopkov's transition to a new job was disagreements with the CENKI management on how to complete the construction of facilities and complexes of the cosmodrome, as well as methods of working with subcontracting organizations.
"It was decided that this would be better for everyone," says one of the top managers involved in the construction of the East.
A government official, for his part, calls the decision strange: "He was one of the best specialists, it will not be easy to find an equivalent replacement."
According to Yu, this will not be necessary: the position of technical director of the cosmodrome will be abolished, and its functions will be scattered on the CENSKI units.
