Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can help ease HCC.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies suggest otherwise: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help alleviate symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
It is an incurable disease that affects an estimated 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leading to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid of the protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase gut tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that the immune cells in the gut make sure that harmful microbes coming from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance while protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much disturbed in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have shown that mice with a specific bacterium in the gut appear to increase cell tolerance.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan - one of the building blocks of protein - to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan was contained in mice' nutrition, the more of these immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation of the environment in the gut.
Postdoc Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying a type of tolerant immune cells, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, and the other group, which belonged to the same line, but was kept separately, they did not have.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the gut microbiomes of mice - communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
Dna from the mice's gut cells was sequenced, and six types of bacteria were found present in mice with immune cells but absent in mice without them.
Mice grown in a sterile environment, did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells, received L. reuteri, and immune cells they appeared.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of fluid - without bacteria - to undived immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of the processing of tryptophan, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mice's food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells also halved.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in genes associated with tryptophan have been found in people suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
She says: "Perhaps we need to strengthen the development of these cells, because inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can potentially lead to an expansion of their population."
