Props for the White House costing taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House's decision last month to bring a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event on U.S. industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as the "Marine One" when the president is on board, was the centerpiece of a July 17 White House event that showcased U.S. construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and top White House officials have surveyed technology products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, manufactured in Connecticut, was on display next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift truck from Mississippi.
According to the First Squadron of Marine Helicopters (HMX-1), the department responsible for helicopter control, the White House Military Administration ordered the presence of a helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO," just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an "unusual" event.
"I just wanted you to make sure you were aware because this is an unusual, high-profile event," the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his chief, the First Deputy Chief of Aviation for the Marine Corps, ahead of the event.
The letter stated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 to attend the 3 p.m. event and would remain there until the lawn was vacated between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to return to flight in accordance with the working hours restrictions.
The first crew escorted the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel remained next to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It is not clear from the recordings obtained by TIME magazine whether a second crew was required in the end.
Hatch's law prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event contradicts this ruling.
"Among other things, we asked if this was a violation of Hatch's law, and we were told not," the commander wrote.
"It looks like you have nowhere to go," the deputy chief replied.
The "Made in America" event was declared by the White House as an official event, and Hatch's law did not apply to it.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the president made efforts to advance health care reform, then in the Senate, and touted attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as "Marine One" and "Air Force One" for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But to request them only in the interests of photo opportunities is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of debate in February when the president drove through the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was inundated with messages complaining about his predecessor's use of the president's plane.
"The White House is thrilled with the "Made in America" screening, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials," said White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington metropolitan area and on the South Lawn to train the Transportation of the President of the United States to the White House with precision to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 held 58 training camps outside the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight performed for the "Made in America" event was counted by the crew in the required training flights for a month.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 extra hours that day as part of "non-presidential support missions."
According to the White House, taxpayers did not bear the cost of any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A Sikorsky spokesperson said that the company did not participate in the demonstration of the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep a budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Defense Department's hourly rate for fiscal year 2017, the Defense Department's reimbursement rate for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit's records stated that the airtime of the aircraft was 30 minutes each way from its airfield at the Marine Corps' Cuantico Air Base in Virginia.
The White House argues that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than this rate.
"It's completely wrong to calculate the cost to taxpayers based on the approximate reimbursement rate," Walters said.
"These approximate rates include personnel, maintenance and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual appropriations."
According to a 2015 study by RAND Corporation, reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and expenses specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of a helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to demonstrate this week things that are done in America," Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I assume, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose workplace depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we're all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to create.
So, of course, it is absolutely appropriate to pay attention to it."
It was unclear whether Trump was interacting with the helicopter while inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he definitely sat in the driver's seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of company products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said. "I have three."
