The National Union of Unskilled, Municipal and Boiler Workers (GMB) is concerned about investment at McVitie's factory in Glasgow
The union is demanding assurances from the managers of biscuit maker McVitie's over its long-term production commitment at the Glasgow plant.
The Scottish branch of GMB reports that the company has been silent on the future of investment at the Toloro facility.
The factory, which produces, among other products, cookies Hobnobs and Rich Tea, employs more than 500 people.
Pladis, the owner of McVitie's, says it has invested more than 5 million pounds in the facility over the past few years.
The company adds that in case of any changes in the work of the facility, employees and representatives of the union "will know about them first."
In a letter to the head of the company's facility, the Scottish branch of GMB demanded that McVitie's response to concerns that funding would not be used to upgrade production lines.
Senior organiser Drew Duffy said: "Members of our union are deeply concerned that we cannot obtain clarity from the chief executive of the business and investment plan for the future of Tolcross."
Families have worked here for generations and the concentration of workers is great in local society and in Greater Glasgow; it is the most important pillar of decent work in the territory of high unemployment and social deprivation.
So in terms of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising living wage and chronic production decline, Glasgow's East End desperately needs the prosperity of manufacturing at McVitie's factory.
A spokeswoman for Pladis said: "The head of the Toltros facility only received a letter yesterday from the Scottish branch of GMB and the company will respond immediately as we value our ongoing cooperation with staff and union representatives."
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting with GMB staff and representatives in Tolcross, where we openly discussed a number of issues.
We talked to our employees about the fact that, as all companies operating in the most competitive and unstable economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our actions - and this applies to all our facilities and activities - to remain competitive.
"In recent years, we have invested more than 5 million pounds in our Tolkoro facility, especially in production lines and improved performance."
We are fully aware of the value of Tolkoros as a production facility, and in case of any changes in the work at this site, employees and representatives of the trade union will be the first to know about it."
