Did PSG warn Barcelona about Neymar's move three years ago?
La Liga player may regret his interest in Marco Verratti
Paris Saint-Germain will not stop chasing Neymar after the club offered 189 million pounds for his buy-out, but did they warn Barcelona of setting a world record three years ago?
The sensational offer revived the summer transfer window when the Ligue 1 club was poised to break the world record for the cost of a move, more than double the previous mark associated with Paul Pogba's return to Manchester United last season for 89 million pounds.
When the transfer is complete, Neymar will become the most expensive player in the world, as well as the highest paid professional athlete in the world, as PSG offer him a salary of more than 500,000 pounds a week net.
Barcelona are known to be furious at the way the offer was made and how Neymar broke his contract, despite the fact that, according to a source close to the Catalan club's management, the club have always done their best for the player since his move from Santos in 2013.
But was the football world not warned of such a possibility three years ago by the president of PSG?
When Manchester City expressed interest in the employment of Blaise Matuidi in 2014, Nasser Al-Khelaifi issued a severe warning to any club that would like to lure one of PSG's best players.
"I'm not worried because they know that if they touch one of our players, then we'll play against them, we'll make offers to their players," Al-Khelaifi said.
"We respect all clubs.
But if they try to recruit one of our players, they will face consequences."
Barcelona appeared to have crossed this line when the Spanish club expressed interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verratti earlier this summer.
PSG have made it clear that they will not let the Italian player go on any terms, and now it is likely that Barcelona feel the consequences of their offer in the form of the loss of one of their most valuable players, Neymar.
